In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert more time and effort to trace, verify and reconcile the balance of Cash in Bank under the Special Education Fund and make appropriate adjustments to correct the abnormal balances;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to activate the dormant depository account maintained for SEF to avoid occurrence of the abnormal balance on the account;

Require the Municipal Accountant to cause the immediate preparation of adjusting journal entries to identify and record all reconciling items identified in the Bank Reconciliation Statements; and 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to cancel the stale checks after exhaustion of all remedies, such as written notices to the payees and submission of the corresponding DVs and supporting documents.  If cancellation is not possible despite written notices, the corresponding amounts of the stale checks may be reverted back to the book balances with the recording of accounts payable.

We recommended that the Management comply strictly with the prescribed controls over PPE as provided for in pertinent laws, rules and regulations. We also recommended to Management the following:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the LGU, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records thru the Inventory Committee created;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE after the inventory taking pursuant to the Section 269 of the GAM for LGUs.

We recommended that the Management:

Conduct physical count of Local Road Networks and prepare the RPCLRN;

Update the Registry of Public Infrastructures, through a detailed review of prior year’s transactions, in order to identify the entire Road Networks of the Municipality;

Complete Local Road Inventory records with Road Map and Local Road Network Property Cards and submit the said Report prepared by the Inventory Committee as shown in Annex A of COA Circular 2015-008; and

Make proper disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements as regards all Road Networks pursuant to COA Circular 2015-008.

We recommended that the Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to update and reconcile the balances reported with the Source Agency immediately and draw adjusting entries as necessary; 

Require the Accountable Officer/s of the said fund transfers to review the implementation of the same and cause the liquidation thereof;

Return/remit to the Source Agency  or National Treasury any unused/unutilized balances relating to the fund transfers; and 

Strictly adhere to COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 19, 1994 and Section 63, Chapter 6 of GAM for NGAs Volume I, relative to the grant, utilization and liquidation of funds transferred to Implementing Agencies.

We recommended that the Management:

Maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund by speeding up the implementation of the prioritized programs, projects and activities funded out of the 20% DF as per Annual Investment Plan and that closer coordination among the officials involved in planning, execution and monitoring be undertaken to achieve the desired level of outcomes;

Instruct the Municipal Planning Development Officer to immediately look into the unimplemented developmental projects as embodied in the Annual Investment Plan to identify causes of non-implementation and to develop feasible and specific solutions to effectively implement developmental project;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to be very prudent, meticulous, conscientious and precise in evaluating the timely implementation of each and every project.  Likewise, he should also conduct regular inspection of the projects so that the accomplishment is monitored and evaluated based on the project implementation schedule as stated in the Annual Investment Plan; and 

Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to submit monthly to the Audit Team a detailed Statement of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances, showing, among others, the individual programs, projects and activities funded with current and continuing appropriations under the 20% Development Fund and to review the balances of current and continuing appropriations at the end of the year for possible inclusion in the annual budget preparation. Unexpended balances of appropriations of projects, programs and activities, which were already completed/accomplished should be re-appropriated for other PPAs of the ensuing year upon recommendation of the Local Chief Executive and approval of the Sanggunian Bayan.

Require the Municipal Accountant to identify the amount and details of the account “Trust Liability-DRRM” presented in the financial statements and reconcile the same with the balances disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to revert the unutilized balances of Special Trust Fund for CY 2012, CY 2013 and CY 2014 to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund;

Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately transfer the unexpended balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE totaling to P2,681,039.00 to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability – DRRM” as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2012-002;

Maintain Subsidiary Ledgers of the Municipality’s unutilized DRRMF to the Special Trust Fund;

Require the Designated MDDRMO to submit the Report on the Sources and Utilization of the LDRRMF duly certified by the Provincial Accountant, through LDRRMC and LDC, to the COA on or before the 15th day after the end of each month to facilitate the timely monitoring of implementation of LDRRMPs and balance of fund, if there is any, by the concerned offices, copy furnished Office of the Civil Defense and the Local Government Operation Officer of the Department of Interior and Local Government; and

Require the Secretariat of the MDRRMC to post the Report and Utilization of LDRRMF in the agency website and in conspicuous places within the Municipality and other areas where the public always convene, for their information.

